</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-7-1.jpg" alt="A surprise assault" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Ukraine has launched a <a target="_blank" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-01-2025-h1-1-counterattack">counterattack</a> in Russia’s Kursk region, targeting multiple locations in a surprise assault. Ukrainian forces, which have held parts of Kursk since August, face resistance from Russian and North Korean troops. Kyiv claims its offensive delivers justice, while Moscow asserts its units repelled the attack near Berdin. The head of the Ukrainian Presidential Office, Andriy Yermak, said, “Kursk region, good news, Russia is getting what it deserves.” The Ukraine military has not publicly confirmed the operation.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Russian Defense Ministry claims to have repelled two assaults. Ukraine aims to strengthen its position before potential negotiations, while Russia questions the strategy behind the incursion. Hundreds of <a target="_blank" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-01-2025-h1-2-north-koreans-have-died">North Koreans have died</a> so far in the Makhnovka village in Kursk. Both sides have taken a lot of losses this winter and are claiming to be ready to end the war; the more significant issue is the agreement on the conditions on how to end the war.</p>
        </mj-text>
