          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Call for independence</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-7-2.jpg" alt="Call for independence" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Greenland’s Prime Minister, Múte Egede, has called for <a target="_blank" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-01-2025-h2-3-independence-from-denmark">independence from Denmark</a> in a New Year’s address, stressing the island’s right to represent itself globally. He hinted at an independence referendum, potentially coinciding with the 2025 April parliamentary election. These remarks came shortly after U.S. President-elect Donald Trump expressed interest in <a target="_blank" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-01-2025-h2-4-purchasing-greenland">purchasing Greenland</a>, calling it a strategic necessity. He rebuffed Trump’s proposal, reaffirming that Greenland is “not for sale.” Denmark was also on the same page. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Greenland has been self-ruling since 1979 but relies on Denmark for foreign and defense policy and receives $519 million in annual subsidies from Copenhagen. So, complete independence would complicate things. Also, losing Danish nationality means losing one of the most powerful passports in the world and access to the EU. However, Greenland is strategically located and rich in minerals, so advocates believe they could be fine without Denmark. This discussion reflects on Denmark’s colonial legacy, which is less in the spotlight than Western Europe's.</p>
        </mj-text>
