          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇹🇼 Taiwan:</strong> Taiwan suspects Chinese involvement in cutting an <a target="_blank" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-01-2025-br1-8-undersea-telecom-cable">undersea telecom cable</a> early Friday. The Cameroon-flagged vessel Shunxin-39, linked to Hong Kong-based Jie Yang Trading Limited owned by Chinese citizen Guo Wenjie, was intercepted by Taiwan's coast guard but evaded boarding due to rough seas and continued toward South Korea. Chunghwa Telecom rerouted traffic to maintain service on the $500 million Trans-Pacific Express cable. Taiwan, frequently targeted in such attacks, has sought EU assistance. These incidents, including Russia's alleged sabotage of a <a target="_blank" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-01-2025-br1-9-finland-estonia-power-cable">Finland-Estonia power cable</a>, highlight rising "gray-zone" aggression testing Western defenses amid geopolitical tensions with China and Russia.
</p>
